Use a symbolic rule engine. At 100 variables, constraint satisfaction is tractable with deterministic solvers (SAT, SMT, or constraint programming). Symbolic engines guarantee solution correctness, provide explanability, and avoid the data-gathering overhead of neural training. Neural modules excel at approximation over massive variables or when constraints are soft/probabilistic—neither applies here. Reserve neural approaches for when symbolic methods timeout or you're combining soft preference learning with hard constraints. If your constraint graph is sparse and propagation-efficient, symbolic scales comfortably to 100 variables.
